TY  - JOUR
AU  - Babina, Tania
AU  - Bernstein, Asaf
AU  - Mezzanotti, Filippo
T1  - Financial Disruptions and the Organization of Innovation: Evidence from the Great Depression
PY  - 2023
Y1  - 2023/11/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhad023
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 36
IS  - 11
SP  - 4271
EP  - 4317
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We examine innovation following the Great Depression using data on a century’s worth of U.S. patents and a difference-in-differences design that exploits regional variation in the crisis severity. Harder-hit areas experienced large and persistent declines in independent patenting, mostly reflecting the disruption in access to finance during the crisis. This decline was larger for young and inexperienced inventors and lower-quality patents. In contrast, innovation by large firms increased, especially among young and inexperienced inventors. Overall, the Great Depression contributed to the decline in technological entrepreneurship and accelerated the shift of innovation into larger firms.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhad023
ER  - 



